https://explainshell.com/explain/1/apropos

LINUX SHELL

    - Generally called the linux terminal
    - interface between users and the kernel for a computer system
    - Text based GUI 

TERMINAL EMULATORS

    - Serves as a interface to the shell interpreter
    - Provides us with different methods and functions to work with the terminal, such as splitting the terminal into one window, working
in multiple directories, creating different workspaces, and much more.
    - An example is Tmux

MOST COMMON SHELL

    - Bourne Again Shell (BASH), it is part of the GNU project.
    - Other shells exist
        - Tcsh/Csh
        - Zsh
        - Ksh
        - Fish

PROMPT DESCRIPTION

    - <username>@<hostname><current_working_directory>$
    - Home directory = ~    (Default when we login)
    - $ stands for a user whil # stands for root user (Priveleged/Unpriveleged)
    - Can customize to display other information such as IP address, date, time, the exit status of the last command etc.
    - Can customize the config file .bashrc for the bash shell

    SPECIAL CHARACTERS FOR CUSTOMIZATION
      - \d                  Date (Mon Feb 6)
      - \D{%Y-%m-%d}        Date (YYYY-MM-DD)
      - \H                  Full hostname
      - \j                  Number of jobs managed by the shell
      - \n                  Newline
      - \r                  Carriage return
      - \s                  Name of the shell
      - \t                  Current time 24-hour (HH:MM:SS)
      - \@                  Current time
      - \u                  Current username
      - \w                  Full path to current working directory

